"I am happy. I can't explain it enough. I thank Kenyans for their support. I am happy to have this place where I can warmly welcome people. I thank God for how far He has brought me," said Ms Kitsao.
She added: "I thank God as the stones (I boiled) have turned to a house. My children are now having their daily meals just like other children."
The new house that was built following contributions by well-wishers, she says, gives her hope that she will never go back to where she was and will forget what she underwent.





Nothing to eat
Eight months ago, Ms Kitsao, a widow and a mother of eight, had been forced to boil stones in the name of cooking to make her hungry children think that a meal was being prepared as she had nothing to feed them on.
“I had nothing to feed my children on and so I decided to put the stones in the sufuria and boil them so that my children would think that I was cooking something for them,” said Ms Kitsao, a resident of Mleji Village in Milango Saba, when she spoke to the Nation back then.
Ms Kitsao had seen suffering following the Covid-19 threat that is wreaking havoc among hundreds of Kenyans and left many fighting for their survival.
Following the highlight of her plight by the media, hundreds of well-wishers came to her rescue to contribute food and money that sustained her and her children.



